<DOC><DOCNO> AP880402-0114 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1644EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-02 0501</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0514</SECOND><HEAD>Rain Drenches Central Gulf Coast, Deep Snow On Western Plains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A storm centered over Kansas spread rain and thunderstorms upand down the Mississippi Valley on Saturday, causing floods andtornadoes in Louisiana and trailing heavy snow across the westernGreat Plains.   Heavy rain accompanied showers and thunderstorms across southernLouisiana into southern Alabama during the morning.   Widespread street flooding was reported across the New Orleansarea and north of Lake Pontchartrain. Rainfall amounts in the NewOrleans area ranged up to 9 inches since Friday evening, with 8.17inches at Gretna and 6.09 inches at Gramercy. In east-centralLouisiana, 5.65 inches fell at Bayou Sorrel.   During the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, 2.08 inches of rain fellat New Orleans' Lakefront Airport.   Strong thunderstorms developed during the afternoon across partsof eastern Iowa and northwestern Illinois. Showers were scatteredfrom western Nebraska through southern Minnesota and northernIllinois, with most rain amounts less than an inch.   Snow and blowing snow made travel difficult in northwesternKansas and northeastern Colorado, and most roads in the western twocounties of the Oklahoma Panhandle were closed.   Snow amounts included 13 inches at Goodland, Kan.; 22 at Timpas,Colo.; 20 at Walsh, Colo.; and up to 23 inches in the OklahomaPanhandle, according to highway officials and the National WeatherService.   Drifts 4 to 5 feet high and wind gusting to 40 mph were reportedacross southeastern Colorado, the weeather service said.   Elsewhere, showers were scattered across the Pacific Northwestas another storm system approached the coast.   Showers were scattered across parts of eastern Georgia extendinginto northeastern Florida. Showers also developed over parts of theupper Ohio Valley.   Dense morning fog slowed travel across northern Illinois andsouthern Wisconsin into northern Indiana.   The fog halted landings at Chicago's O'Hare airport for abouttwo hours early in the morning, said Joe Hopkins of UnitedAirlines, the airport's largest carrier. By 9:30 a.m., whenvisibility was about a quarter of a mile at O'Hare, United hadcancelled about 90 flights out of 800 scheduled because of the fog,he said.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 33degrees at Imperial, Neb., to 86 at Thermal, Calif. The low for theday was 10 degrees at Lake Yellowstone, Wyo.   For Sunday, widespread showers and thunderstorms were forecastfrom the Great Lakes through the Ohio and Tennessee valleys to thecentral Gulf of Mexico coast. Widespread showers also were forecastover the northern Pacific Coast with scattered showers inland.   Highs in the 40s were predicted from northeastern Minnesota intoUpper Michigan; in the 50s across south-central and easternColorado, the upper Mississippi Valley, the upper Great Lakes andmuch of New England, and across the Pacific Northwest; in the 80sfrom the desert Southwest across southern Texas into the lowerMississippi Valley, and across much of the Florida Peninsula; andin the 60s or 70s across much of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>